article.description: Candice Wiggins scored 19 points to lead the Minnesota Lynx in 92-78 win over the Tulsa Shock on Saturday night, completing a sweep of the team's home-and-home series.
article.headline: Lynx ratchet up defense to secure sweep of Shock
article.linkText: Lynx finish off home-and-home sweep of Shock
article.story:
TULSA, Okla. -- Candice Wiggins scored 19 points to lead the Minnesota Lynx in a 92-78 win over the Tulsa Shock on Saturday night, completing a sweep of the team's home-and-home series.

Lindsay Whalen had 17 points and six assists, Seimone Augustus scored 16 points and Rebekkah Brunson added 14 points and 11 rebounds for the Lynx (4-9). Minnesota won the teams' season series 3-2, including a 78-67 win at home on Friday night.

"Our goal was to sweep Tulsa in these two games and we were very focused on that goal," Lynx coach Cheryl Reeve said. "We knew that by doing that, it would set the stage for taking us to the next level. We accomplished that and are ready to move forward."

The Lynx shot 51 percent from the field, including 12 for 19 (63 percent) on 3-pointers, and finished with 21 assists and 12 steals. The Shock had 21 turnovers.

"We didn't turn the ball over," Reeve said. "We forced them into turnovers. A combination of all those things translated into a win over us."

Having Wiggins and Augustus also made a difference. Augustus missed the teams' first three meetings and Wiggins made her season debut in the third matchup on June 4.

"No question," Reeve said. "When Tulsa is going to play that zone, whether its 1-3-1 or 1-1-3, it just puts us in a situation where we had some wide open looks. I trust those players every single time they take it. It's got a great chance to go in."

Scholanda Robinson scored 14 points, Alexis Hornbuckle had 12 and Natasha Lacy and Kara Braxton added 10 each for Tulsa (3-8), which lost its fifth straight. The Shock are winless since beating the Lynx 92-79 on June 4 in their previous home game.

"In the last game [at the BOK Center], the third quarter got away from us," Reeve said. "Efficiency on offense is the name of the game when we play the Tulsa Shock. We certainly, with it being the fifth time we played them, we kind of solved the puzzle. We got wide-open shots and we made them. That's a big key."

Former world-class sprinter Marion Jones tied a season high with four points in 10-plus minutes for Tulsa after going scoreless in 1 minute Friday night at Minnesota.

Minnesota made seven consecutive 3s in the first half after Charde Houston missed the team's first attempt.

"That was incredible shooting with the basketball," Tulsa coach Nolan Richardson said. "Even if you have nobody guarding, you're not going to make seven out of eight. But they did and they shot extremely well throughout the ball game."

Houston's jumper started a 10-2 run for the Lynx in the final minute of the second quarter and Brunson capped it with a layup to stretch Minnesota's lead to 55-42 with about 6 1/2 minutes left in the third.

Shanna Crossley followed with a 3-pointer for the Shock, but the Lynx scored the next seven points to increase the advantage to 17 on Hamchetou Maiga-Ba's layup with 4:22 to go in the quarter.

"It wasn't just the zone that wasn't working," Richardson said. "It was the man-to-man wasn't working, the 2-1-2 wasn't working, nothing was."

Crossley had consecutive baskets and Braxton had a layup to pull Tulsa to 67-57 with 1:15 left in the third, but got no closer. Wiggins made two 3s in an 10-1 run that stretched the Lynx's lead to 85-66 with 3:41 to go in the fourth.
